  "texts": [
    "Gao et al. [73], Mou et al.",
    "[74], and Wang et al. [75] offer frameworks for classifying simulation purposes, agent architectures, and evaluation criteria.",
    "All three emphasize the importance of distinguishing between simulation layers: individual cognition, interaction-level dynamics, and macro-level outcomes such as polarization or norm formation.",
    "Mou et al. [74] argue that simulations can support both theory building and policy exploration, particularly in settings where direct experimentation is infeasible.",
    "Gao et al. [73] broaden the field's scope to include socio-technical and cyber-physical systems, noting that LLMs are uniquely suited for simulating text-based interaction."
